/*
==============================================================
DOUBLY LINKED LIST NOTES
==============================================================

1) What is a Doubly Linked List?
--------------------------------------------------------------
- A doubly linked list is a linked list where each node has:
  1. prev pointer
  2. data
  3. next pointer

- prev points to previous node
- next points to next node
- It can move in both directions

Diagram:
null <- [10] <-> [20] <-> [30] -> null

--------------------------------------------------------------

2) Structure of One Node
--------------------------------------------------------------
Each node has 3 parts:

+---------+---------+---------+
|  prev   |  data   |  next   |
+---------+---------+---------+

- prev = address of previous node
- data = actual value
- next = address of next node

--------------------------------------------------------------

3) Main Difference from Singly Linked List
--------------------------------------------------------------
- In singly LL, each node has only next
- In doubly LL, each node has both prev and next
- So backward traversal is possible in doubly LL

--------------------------------------------------------------

4) Meaning of Head and Tail
--------------------------------------------------------------
- head is the first node
- tail is the last node

Important:
- head.prev is always null
- tail.next is always null

Diagram:
head                               tail
 |                                  |
 v                                  v
null <- [10] <-> [20] <-> [30] -> null

--------------------------------------------------------------

5) Traversal in Doubly Linked List
--------------------------------------------------------------
Forward traversal:
head -> next -> next

Backward traversal:
tail -> prev -> prev

Example:
null <- [10] <-> [20] <-> [30] -> null

Forward:
10 -> 20 -> 30

Backward:
30 -> 20 -> 10

--------------------------------------------------------------

6) Why Doubly LL is Useful
--------------------------------------------------------------
- Easy backward movement
- Deletion is easier when node is given
- Useful in browser history, undo/redo, LRU cache

--------------------------------------------------------------

7) Insertion Idea
--------------------------------------------------------------
To insert a node in doubly LL,
we usually update 4 links carefully:
- newNode.prev
- newNode.next
- previous node's next
- next node's prev

Example: insert 25 between 20 and 30

Before:
null <- [10] <-> [20] <-> [30] -> null

After:
null <- [10] <-> [20] <-> [25] <-> [30] -> null

--------------------------------------------------------------

8) Deletion Idea
--------------------------------------------------------------
To delete a node,
connect previous node and next node directly.

Before:
null <- [10] <-> [20] <-> [30] -> null

Delete 20

After:
null <- [10] <-> [30] -> null

Changes:
- 10.next = 30
- 30.prev = 10

--------------------------------------------------------------

9) Advantages of Doubly Linked List
--------------------------------------------------------------
- Can traverse in both directions
- Easier deletion compared to singly LL
- Helpful when previous node is needed

--------------------------------------------------------------

10) Disadvantages of Doubly Linked List
--------------------------------------------------------------
- Extra memory needed for prev pointer
- More pointer updates
- Slightly more complex than singly LL

--------------------------------------------------------------

11) Time Complexity
--------------------------------------------------------------
Operation                  Time
--------------------------------------------------------------
Forward Traversal          O(n)
Backward Traversal         O(n)
Insert at beginning        O(1)
Insert at end              O(n)   // O(1) if tail is maintained
Delete at beginning        O(1)
Delete at end              O(n)   // O(1) if tail is maintained
Delete given node          O(1)   // if node reference is given

--------------------------------------------------------------

12) Real Interview One-Liner
--------------------------------------------------------------
A doubly linked list is a linear data structure
where each node stores prev, data, and next pointers,
allowing traversal in both forward and backward directions.

--------------------------------------------------------------

13) Very Short Revision Note
--------------------------------------------------------------
- Node = prev + data + next
- head.prev = null
- tail.next = null
- forward and backward traversal possible
- more flexible than singly LL
- extra memory used for prev

--------------------------------------------------------------

